		<text id="swap_text01" x="575" y="110" width="195" height="" autosize="H" style="REFERENCE" visible="false" fx="INTRO_SHOW" hidefx="INTRO_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;You're right. Though each child is unique, you should clarify the general timeline of language development with parents so that they have an informed perspective on their own child's progress.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;At age 2, children should be experiencing a vocabulary spurt and should be pro-active in their attempts at communication. If a 2-year-old produces only few words and does not seem to be progressing in his language development, he may need further evaluation. &lt;/P&gt;</content>
		</text>
		<text id="swap_text02" x="" y="" width="195" height="" autosize="H" style="REFERENCE" visible="false" fx="INTRO_SHOW" hidefx="INTRO_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Right. Asking children questions and waiting for their replies is an excellent way to encourage the development of language skills.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Everyday interactions offer the best opportunities to assist a child in language development. Parents should talk to their child about their day and explain what they are doing as they perform everyday activities. Word games, rhyming, and singing are also fun and effective ways to help children develop language skills.&lt;/P&gt;</content>
		</text>
		<text id="swap_text03" x="584" y="112" width="183" height="" autosize="H" style="REFERENCE" visible="false" fx="INTRO_SHOW" hidefx="INTRO_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">Try again.</content>
